clickRoutine.note: First figure out who is moving and retrieve the appropriate CSS for use in the squares.
Now use the row/column information placed there by the edge that called us
clickRoutine.note1: to identify that button; put it in the invoker collection

clickRoutine.note: Compute the constants corresponding to the neighboring rows and columns
Next, compute the edges of the square to the left (or above for rowButton)
clickRoutine.note1: and put them in cell1, cell2, and cell3

clickRoutine.note: Create a collection containing the three other edges of the square
and count the number of black borders of that square
numBorders1 (for one of the squares) is true if and only if
clickRoutine.note1: there are less then three black borders (to be used for skipping)

clickRoutine.note: Compute the identifier of the relevant square
Fill in the square if all edges are black
Retrieve the label for the score of the current player
Increment the score if not skipping
Moving on to the other square, do the same things as above
And again change the square's color if appropriate
Increment score again if appropriate
Set the color of the invoking edge to black
and remember in a property that it has been played in this game
Compute a boolean to decide if we should switch players (true)

colButton.note1: Collect the three adjacent edges for each possible box
colButton.note2: into cell1, cell2, cell3. Determine how many have been clicked
colButton.note3: and use that to decide (numBorders1 and numBorders2) whether
colButton.note4: either or both squares should be shaded.
colButton.note5: As necessary, reverse the current player and the arrow.
colButton.note6: css for the two colors is stored in the `reset` button,
colButton.note7: as are the current and other player colors

clickRoutine.note: Compute a boolean to decide if we should switch players (true)

rowButton.note1: Collect the three adjacent edges for each possible box
rowButton.note2: into cell1, cell2, cell3. Determine how many have been clicked
rowButton.note3: and use that to decide (numBorders1 and numBorders2) whether
rowButton.note4: either or both squares should be shaded.
rowButton.note5: As necessary, reverse the current player and the arrow.
rowButton.note6: css for the two colors is stored in the reset button,
rowButton.note: See colButton for documentation of what this does.
rowButton.note7: as are the ids for the current and other players.

reset.css: background: white; color: black; font-family: Arial; font-size: 18px; border-color: black; border-width: 2px

Now set the proper player in the code

info.description: Add lines to complete squares.  Most completed squares wins.

8muz.text:
1. Click the oval edges surrounding the squares.

2. If you do not completely surround a square with your move, 
    it is then the other player's turn.

3. If you do, the color of the square changes to your color, 
    and you get to move again.
